WEBVTT

NOTE
San Diego County Wildfire Burn Demonstration — AF31 vs Ammonium Polyphosphate Retardant
Duration: ~4 minutes 40 seconds

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:20.000
[Aerial drone footage of San Diego County natural vegetation — open landscape with dry brush and shrubs]

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:45.000
[Area treated with Ammonium Polyphosphate Based Retardant — the pink powder used by aerial firefighting aircraft]

00:00:45.000 --> 00:01:10.000
[Controlled burn initiated — vegetation treated with ammonium polyphosphate retardant ignites and burns]

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:35.000
[Drone footage shows burned, scorched area where standard retardant was applied — plants destroyed]

00:01:35.000 --> 00:02:00.000
[Camera shifts to adjacent area pre-treated with AF31 — same natural vegetation, same conditions]

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:30.000
[Controlled burn applied to AF31 treated area — vegetation resists fire, significantly reduced combustion]

00:02:30.000 --> 00:03:00.000
[On-screen text: "Non-toxic — no heavy chemicals" — AF31 highlighted as a safe alternative to traditional retardants]

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:30.000
[Time-lapse or follow-up footage: 8 weeks after AF31 pre-treatment — vegetation in treated area alive and recovering]

00:03:30.000 --> 00:04:00.000
[On-screen text: "Healthy fuel moisture, vibrant green color" — treated plants show green growth 8 and 12 weeks post-application]

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:20.000
[Drone footage comparing the scorched retardant zone with the green, living AF31 treated zone side by side]

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:40.000
[Firefighter demonstrates frontline application of AF31 using a portable extinguisher — simple, accessible deployment shown]
